<DOCNO> XIE19961204.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainians Cool Over Government Plan to Sell Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 3 (Xinhua) -- "I just cannot afford to pay the
rent", said Ulia, a 22-year-old Ukrainian woman. "How can I afford
to buy an apartment ?" she asked despairingly.
</P>
<P>
Ulia hasn't been paid for a year. Her husband is out of a job
and she owes the government 400 U.S. dollars in rent. Not
surprisingly she is cool to new plans by the government to ease the
country's housing crisis by giving Ukrainians loans or subsidies
to buy their own homes.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to set up a special organization to raise
funds to provide these loans or subsidies to help people buy their
own homes.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has also agreed to provide loans to three
Ukrainian cities for residential construction. The houses will be
sold to private buyers.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes these schemes will go some way to easing
the country's acute housing shortage and form part of a program
to transfer the state-owned property industry into a private
market-led industry.
</P>
<P>
Some five million households are living in dormitories and
2.5 million families and single people are queuing up for
a roof over their heads.
</P>
<P>
But with the country facing an economic crisis as it undergoes
transition from a centrally planned to a market economy, the
cash-strapped government has been powerless to help.
</P>
<P>
As national and company funds are short, Ukraine's residential
construction has shrunk by 200 percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has only built 7.5 million square meters of residential
houses this year, compared with 8.3 million square meters last
year, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Under the old centrally planned economy Ukrainians used to get
an apartment from the government and pay a small rent. But as the
country moved to a market economy and experienced the traumas of
the transition, the housing market is in chaos.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the 51,748,000 Ukrainians have not paid
their rent, complaining of wage delays and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Official unemployment in Ukraine remains very low, under one
percent. But the collapse of the Soviet command economy has left
many people technically jobless because their factories or coal
mines sit idle.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's government has pledged to pay the 1.8 billion
U.S. dollars in back wages it is estimated to owe state
workers. But it has been slow to come up with the funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
