<HEADLINE> Kirghizia to Cut Civil Servants, Ministries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,000 civil servants
in Kirghizia are to be sacked and the number of government
ministries slashed by almost a third from 22 to 16 as part of a
government austerity and efficiency drive, reports reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
Kirghiz President Askar Akayev issued the orders in a decree,
reports cited the Kirghiz presidential press service as saying.
</P>
<P>
Akayev promised in a nationwide televised message last month to
have "excessive and corrupted apparatchiks (civil servants)"
considerably reduced as they had begun to impede the economy's
transformation.
</P>
<P>
"The massive...corrupted apparatus of officials began in recent
years to impede...market reforms and to discredit the policy of
the state regarding economic transformation," said the president.
</P>
<P>
According to decrees signed by Akayev, the ministries of
economics, transport, water resources and culture will be merged
into other ministries, while the geology and tourism ministries
will become self-supporting agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
