<HEADLINE> Leading Economic Indicators Rose 0.1 Percent in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The composite index of leading
indicators, a main gauge of business cycle of the U.S., increased
0.1 percent in October to 103.6, the Conference Board reported
today.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest point ever since the index was initialized.
The index stood at 100 in 1987.
</P>
<P>
The New York based research group said that the leading
economic index increased 0.2 percent in September and 0.1 percent
in August. Over the six months from April to October, the index
rose 1.3 percent. During this period, eight of the 11 leading
economic indicators advanced.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board's calculations show that six of the 11
leading economic indicators rose in October. The most significant
increases ranged from stock prices to manufacturers' new orders of
consumer goods and materials. The most significant negative
contributor to the composite leading index in October is average
factory workweek.
</P>
<P>
Starting from December 30, the Conference Board will use new
revised factors for computing the indexes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
