<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Differences Resolved on EU Monetary Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Finance
Ministers on Monday resolved most of their differences over a
stability pact to require low budget deficits after monetary
union, local media reported here today.
</P>
<P>
All 15 EU members have accepted in principle a pact under which
fines would be imposed on states that surpass the single-currency
deficit maximum of three percent of their GDP.
</P>
<P>
But there is still disagreement over how and when fines will be
applied and the definition of "exceptional and temporary" economic
circumstances that would allow a country's budget deficit to
exceed this limit.
</P>
<P>
The stability pact is the final major technical building block
to monetary union. EU leaders have been aiming for an accord
to sustain the momentum toward a single currency when they meet in
Dublin later this month.
</P>
<P>
Officials said progress had been made on several parts of the
pact, including the imposition of fines on countries which report an
excessive budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The unresolved issue at this ministerial meeting centered on
Germany's demands to severely limit the circumstances in
which countries would be allowed to run an excessive budget
deficit.
</P>
<P>
Germany wants a strict numerical definition of such
circumstances. It wants the magnitude of such an extraordinary
decline in growth to be specified at two percent, but other
countries have said the figure is too rigid.
</P>
<P>
The ministers have agreed to meet again in Dublin of Ireland on
December 12 to make a last-ditch effort for preparation of an
agreement which could be ratified by EU leaders at a summit
meeting that begins the following day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
