<HEADLINE> US New Home Sales Down Sharply in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- New home sales in the U.S.
plunged by 8.7 percent in October to the lowest level in seven
months, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
Each of the regions in the country shared in the loss which was
seen by analysts as fresh evidence of a moderating U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department said that sales of single-family homes
totaled a seasonally adjusted 714,000 annual rate, down sharply
from 782,000 in September. The sales were the lowest since a
713,000 rate last March when the sales plummeted by 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales slumped by 32.3 percent in the Northeast, the
steepest since they dropped by 33.6 percent in May 1993. Sales
fell by 11.3 percent in the Midwest, the biggest since February
1995. They were off by 8.9 percent in the West and 0.6 percent in
the South.
</P>
<P>
Still, sales in October remained above 700,000 for a 10th
straight month and they are 13.5 percent higher than those in the
first 10 months of last year.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted estimate of new homes for sale was
336,000 at the end of September, representing a supply of 5.6
months at the current sales rate, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. department reported late last month that existing home
sales in the country also dropped in October, the fifth straight
monthly decline.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Association of Home Builders said today that
a membership survey showed a four-point drop in its Housing Market
Index last month.
</P>
<P>
President Randy Smith of the association said the decline was
consistent with the general economic and housing slowdown that was
expected during the second half of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
