<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Shiite Leaders Condemn Armed Attack on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih
Berri denounced here today an armed attack on a prominent Muslim
Shiite leader in Najaf last week, calling it an "infringement
against a religious symbol."
</P>
<P>
Berri, leader of Lebanon's moderate Shiite Amal Movement,
congratulated Grand Ayatollah Ali Husseini Sistani's survival from
the November 25 attack on the Iraqi Shiite chief's house in the
city holy to Shiite Muslims the world over.
</P>
<P>
One of Sistani's attendants was killed and two others were
wounded when unidentified gunmen fired at the house, the
Lebanese house speaker told his visitors in his office.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Lebanese Higher Islamic Shiite
Council headed by Sheikh Mohammed Mahdi Shamseddin said that "A
group of wicked assailants, disguised in clerical attire, stormed
the headquarters of Grand Ayatollah Ali Sistani and opened fire,
killing one person and wounding several others."
</P>
<P>
The council said Ayatollah Sistani "represents the wise and
enlightened (Shiite) authority that Muslims feel should be
protected."
</P>
<P>
It demanded that the assailants be exposed and punished
severely so that others like them will be deterred from carrying
out similar crimes and so that the integrity of Najaf will be
maintained.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, spiritual leader of the
Iranian-backed Shiite Hezbollah, or Party of God, issued a
statement accusing the Iraqi regime of being behind the attack
and held it responsible for Sistani's safety.
</P>
<P>
Ayatollah Sistani is the most senior religious scholar
residing in Najaf, which had been a main center of Shiite
scholars and disciplines until the Iranian holy city of Qom rose
to prominence in the wake of Iran's 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Sistani is a colleague of Lebanon's Sheikh Shamseddin and
Sheikh Fadlallah. All three were students of Ayatollah Abu
Al-Qasem Al-Khoei, who died three years ago in Najaf.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, Ayatollah Al-Khoei's son, Mohammed Taqi, died in
a mysterious car accident near Karbala in south Iraq.
</P>
<P>
After the armed attack last week, the Iraqi government sent a
delegation to Sistani's house in Najaf to apologize for the
incident which was blamed on "thieves", according to local press
reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
