<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ground Forces Chief Suspended, Not Sacked Yet: Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A Kremlin spokesman today denied
Russia's Ground Forces Commander-in-Chief Vladimir Semyonov had
been sacked, saying that so far, he had only been suspended.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing in the Kremlin, Yeltsin's spokesman
Sergei Yastrzhembsky said that Semyonov will remain suspended from
his post until another decree is issued.
</P>
<P>
The special commission charged with all military appointments,
chaired by Defense Council Secretary Yuri Baturin, will study
whether such a decree is appropriate, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Defense Ministry said on Monday that Semyonov had
been fired by President Boris Yeltsin for "actions discrediting
the honor and dignity of a serviceman."
</P>
<P>
However, on Monday night, Yeltsin's Press Service stated that
the Defense Ministry's statement was too hasty. It said Defense
Minister Igor Rodionov had requested the President to dismiss
Semyonov and that Yeltsin had only "agreed in principle."
</P>
<P>
Only with a final decision adopted by the special commission ,
will the President sign the decree, the press service said.
</P>
<P>
According to the press center of the Ground Forces, Semyonov was
summoned by the Defense Minister on November 29 and "informed
of his dismissal."
</P>
<P>
The decision came as "a complete surprise to Semyonov" and "he
does not agree with the wording of the reason for his dismissal,"
the press center said.
</P>
<P>
Semyonov met Baturin later on Monday in a bid to get more
information about the reasons for his sudden dismissal. But
Baturin turned out to be "unaware of the general's dismissal,"
the press center said.
</P>
<P>
Semyonov also told Izvestia (an independent newspaper) that the
Defense Minister had failed to present any formal charges, but
only hinting that the General is unlawfully involved in the
commercial activities of his wife Madlena Semyonova.
</P>
<P>
Madlena works at the Moscow representative office of the
Rosvertol helicopter manufacturer which supplies Mi combat and
cargo helicopters to the Russian army.
</P>
<P>
There is no evidence that Semyonov could have engaged in any
commercial activities for Rosvertol, Izvestia's chief military
correspondent Viktor Litivkin said.
</P>
<P>
Semyonov, 56, who became the Commander-in-Chief of Russia's
Ground Forces in 1991, was once considered as a possible
successor to the former Defense Minister Pavel Grachev.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that Semyonov's removal is in line with
Rodionov's drive to replace loyalists of his predecessor Grachev
with his own proteges. Rodionov may need his own men to push
forward military reform, which plans to cut Russia's
1.5-million-strong armed forces by 300,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
