<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Calls for Removing Trade Barriers in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Executive Secretary
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC), Kaire
Mbuende, has exepressed concern at the slow pace of removing
barriers to free trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende made the call today in Windhoek, capital of Namibia,
when he was speaking at a three-day workshop on the effects of
opening up trade in maize and beef within five SADC member states
of Namibia, Botswana, South Africa, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said the freeing of trade in the SADC will improve food
security by making available cheaper imports, Radio Namibia
reported.
</P>
<P>
But he said SADC must also ensure cheaper imports do not undermine
agriculture, and the member states must strive to attract foreign
investment to the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Such a move will increase the financial viability of the
sector and facilitate transfer of technilogy, the SADC offciial
added.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was organised by the Namibia Economic Policy
Research Unit.
</P>
<P>
SADC comprises Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Namibia, South African, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
</TEXT>
