<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Continues to Grow Slowly in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The manufacturing industry in
Britain expanded for the sixth month running in November, but the
pace of recovery remained slow, according to the latest monthly
survey by the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply.
</P>
<P>
The institute's purchasing managers' index, a composite of
order books, output, stocks, delivery times and employment, fell
marginally last month to 54.4 from 54.5 in October. Any reading
over 50 indicates the sector is growing.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that factory order books were improving at
their fastest rate for two years and although the pound's recent
strength had dented factory orders from overseas, greater demand
from domestic customers was more than compensating.
</P>
<P>
Makers of consumer goods were seeing the biggest rise in
orders, as they had throughout the recent upturn in growth, but
orders for investment goods, such as expensive machinery and
components, were more sluggish, the report indicated.
</P>
<P>
Factory output continued to rise but at a slightly slower rate
than in October, the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
Encouragingly, the strength of the pound, which rose about 10
percent between August and November, is also helping to keep
downward pressure on industry's raw material costs which fell for
the 13th month running in November.
</P>
<P>
"The recent increase in deflationary pressures was almost
entirely a result of the stronger pound making imported inputs
cheaper in sterling terms," the institute said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the survey may help Chancellor of the
Exchequer Kenneth Clarke to resist any Bank of England demands for
higher base rates at the next monetary meeting on December 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
