<HEADLINE> Lott Re-Elected Senate Republican Majority Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Republicans
today re-elected Senator Trent Lott of Mississippi their majority
leader in the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
The senators also selected their other leaders, all without
opposition and by acclamation, said Lott's press secretary, Susan
Irby.
</P>
<P>
Lott, 55, replaced Bob Dole as Republican leader last June,
when Dole resigned to concentrate on his now failed presidential
bid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Democrats were expected to choose Senator Tom
Daschle as minority leader. Daschle, who will turn 49 next Monday,
would begin his third year as minority leader. He won his post by
a single vote two years ago over Senator Christopher Dodd, a
Democrat from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
Each party's senators were choosing their leaders in separate,
closed-door meetings in the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
This year the Republicans' 53-47 Senate majority in the
previous Congress has expanded to 55-45 in the 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles retained his position today,
while Connie Mack was chosen for the No. 3 job of conference
chairman. Mack replaces Thad Cochran who promised not to seek the
job again after Lott defeated him for the top job by a 44-8
vote last June.
</P>
<P>
Also expected to return to their jobs on the Democratic side
are Senators Wendell Ford of Kentucky, the whip, and Barbara Mikulski
of Maryland, who is conference secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
