<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-03 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM to Attend Friends of Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri is scheduled to leave Beirut on December 13 for Washington
to attend the Friends of Lebanon Conference scheduled to be held
on December 16.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed official sources close to the prime minister
today said that Hariri will be accompanied by Foreign Minister
Farez Boueiz, Economy and Trade Minister Yassin Jaber and Fuad
Sinyoura, Minister of State for Financial Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The conference, a forum of donor countries on aid to Lebanon,
took its shape when the United States was negotiating an interim
cease-fire arrangement between Lebanon and Israel in April, which
ended a 17-day Israeli blitz in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hariri and his delegation will present some 31 reconstruction
projects to be executed in the next five years, the cost of which
is put at 5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has invited some 30 countries to
take part in the conference, including all the European Union
countries, oil-rich Arab states, some Asian countries like Japan
and Malaysia as well as leading international lending
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Despite the high political and financial hopes vested in the
conference, the Lebanese government is playing down expectations
for the Washington conference.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Boueiz said recently that he and Hariri
foresaw difficulties in winning a financial harvest in the
conference due partly to the prevailing political climate in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He also said some countries may not fulfill their pledges
because of budgetary or bureaucratic obstacles while other
countries may consider "past contributions as part of the plan."
</P>
<P>
In addition to 5 billion dollars in soft loans and
grants to finance the reconstruction projects, Lebanon will also
call for guarantee facilities of 1 billion dollars for the
government to gain further financing from international capital
market.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by the government said that it hopes
"donors will indicate amounts they undertake to provide in the
form of grants and soft loans and the sectors and projects they
are interested in funding."
</P>
<P>
The report stated the sectors covered by the Friends of
Lebanon conference are those in which private investments are not
usually forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
It said investment will still be encouraged in areas more
compatible to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The report also outlined 31 projects and their costs to
facilitate the participants in the Friends of Lebanon Conference
to study and select.
</P>
<P>
Two infrastructure projects comprise a two-year project to
reduce pollution from three oil-fired electricity plants and a
five-year rehabilitation and development program for the
country's 3,520 kilometers of roads and the construction of 630
kilometers of new roads.
</P>
<P>
These projects cost 1.3 billion dollars, accounting for more
than one fifth of the 5 billion dollars hoped for.
</P>
<P>
Seven projects of social infrastructure at a cost of 1,08
billion dollars cover the construction of new schools,
vocational and technical centers, universities, hospitals and
low-cost housing.
</P>
<P>
The Dams and Water Transport program aims to supply water for
the Greater Beirut area by constructing a dam along the Awali
river and water pipes at a combined cost of 305 million dollars,
and a further 215 million dollars will be spent on building
irrigation dams and lakes.
</P>
<P>
The Water Supply program consists of a 540 million-dollar
project to complete the water and wastewater distribution
network, and a 130 million-dollar project to utilize the ground
water resources of the Anane basin to supply water to south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector will have 400 million dollars
allocated towards eight individual projects
</P>
<P>
The 200 million-dollar Public facilities and Institutions
program includes a 65 million-dollar project of constructing a
100,000-square-meter training center for police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
