<HEADLINE> Greek Farmers Reject Government Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Greek farmers, who started
protest Thursday by blocking highways and the rail link between
Athens and Salonika, rejected today a package of measures put
forward by Agriculture Minister Stephanos Tzoumakas.
</P>
<P>
Tzoumakas, after chairing a meeting with representatives of
agricultural cooperatives, announced Monday night a number of
measures to satisfy the farmers' demands, which include a
40 drachma (about 0.17 U.S. dollar) increase for a kilogram of
cotton, favorable terms for settlement of outstanding debts and a
freezing of current debts. He also promised to ask the European
Commission for increased subsidies for stockbreeders.
</P>
<P>
Farmers said that they would continue their protests and
holding out for a meeting with the prime minister, who is due back
from Lisbon tonight.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, farmers in the Peloponnese decided to erect a
road block on the Patras-Pyrgos and Patras-Tripoli national road,
bringing the number of blockades around the country to more than
35.
</P>
<P>
By cutting all main roads leading to the major cities,
including Salonika, Patras, Aegio, Arta, Ioannina, and Xanthi, one
third of the country's transportation is now paralyzed. Serious
problem in distribution of goods throughout the country is
beginning to emerge.
</P>
<P>
The farmers demand lower fuel costs, lower value added tax on
farm equipment, higher price supports, especially for cotton, and
rescheduling 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in debts at state banks.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural minister said the demands put forward by the
farmers would cost 1 trillion drachmas (4.34 billion U.S.
dollars). "There is simply no such money," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Acting government spokesman Yiannis Nikolaou said today that
there is no question of Prime Minister Costas Simitis meeting with
protesting farmers. He called on organizers of the mobilizations
and the farmers to be aware that their actions created problems
affecting other social groups, and stop the protest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
