<HEADLINE> Newark City Ex-Police Chief Sentenced to 30 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- William R. Celester, former
police director of Newark City in New Jersey State, was sentenced
Monday to 30 months in prison for corruption, the New York Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Celester arrived in the scandal-plagued city of Newark in 1991
amid high hopes that he would improve the troubled police force.
But contrary to the hopes of the citizens, he made the police
force worse.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, Celester admitted in Federal Court that he
had taken 29,500 U.S. dollars from the bank account of the Police
Department, which was used for vocations to foreign countries and
gifts for his wife and girl friends.
</P>
<P>
He also admitted that he had kept 27,000 dollars improperly
donated by police subordinates at a 100-dollar-a-ticket fund
raiser in 1993. He used part of the money to buy a home in Newark
and to pay for trips to the Caribbeans.
</P>
<P>
He also admitted to filing a false Federal tax return in 1993.
He pleaded guilty to three fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
At the hearing, Celester told Judge Garrett E. Brown Jr. of
United States District Court in Trenton that he wanted to
apologize what he had put his family through.
</P>
<P>
Faith S. Hochberg, the United States Attorney for New Jersey,
said afterwards that she was satisfied with the 30-month prison
term. "The message is that if you are a top law enforcement
officer," she said, "you must yourself obey the law." 
</P>
</TEXT>
