<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Attorney General Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Attorney General
Michael Ben-Yair resigned today under alleged pressure from the
government which was angered by his actions against several senior
officials.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Yair made the decision to resign two days ago and
submitted his resignation today to Justice Minister Tzahi
Hanegbi. He is to step down on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Announcing his dramatic resignation, Ben-Yair cited "the huge
workload and intensive activities under both the previous
government and current government" for his decision. He denied
any political pressure behind his move which he said was taken on
his personal initiative.
</P>
<P>
The attorney general's resignation created an uproar in the
country as the opposition was quick to blame the Likud government
for forcing him to resign because of his legal actions against
several senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Yair, appointed by the previous Labor government three
years ago, has been at odds with the Likud government since it
came to power in June.
</P>
<P>
His decision in June to indict current Agriculture Minister
Rafael Eitan, head of Tsomet Party and an election partner of
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, angered the Likud party which
refused to grant him the portfolio of justice minister.
</P>
<P>
Eitan was suspected of violating the Privacy Protection Law by
illegally extracting confidential documents from the Army
computers in order to force a Tsomet activist to leave the party.
</P>
<P>
Later Ben-Yair caused ripples within the Likud coalition when
he decided to investigate the alleged crimes by former Justice
Minister Ya'acov Ne'eman and Likud's Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert.
</P>
<P>
Ne'eman was forced to resign in August after Ben-Yair decided
to open a criminal investigation against him for allegedly
obstructing justice during the investigation of Aryeh Deri, a
Member of the Knesset (Parliament) from the Shas Party.
</P>
<P>
And hawkish Olmert was even more angry about the investigation
of his alleged fundraising scam eight years ago when he served as
the Likud Treasurer.
</P>
<P>
Labor's Knesset coalition Chairman Ra'anan Cohen denounced the
Likud government for forcing Ben-Yair to resign, saying this was
a blow to the country's democracy and the legal system.
</P>
<P>
But Likud coalition head Michael Eitan defended the
government's position, saying Ben-Yair received due respect from
the current government although it did not wanted to appoint him.
</P>
<P>
The Likud government is expected to appoint a new attorney
general soon, but Israeli legal experts are worried that if the
government would make a political decision or a professional
one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961204.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rise of Dollar Against Franc Boosts French Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The abrupt rise of the U.S.
dollar against the French franc today boosted the values of French
stocks to a record high since February 2, 1994, and greatly
encouraged French and foreign investors to spend money on French
shares.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 Index of the Paris Bourse rose by 1.31 percent at
the end of the day today to 2,349.11, after attaining 2,358.65 two
hours and half before the closing of the stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Other European stock markets, including Frankfurt, Amsterdam
and Madrid, also attained new record highs in stocks value today.
</P>
<P>
Debates over the monetary policies of the governments and the
future European Monetary Union in France and Germany have doped
the dollar against European currencies, as France and Germany are
more and more troubled by stagnancy in economic growth and high
unemployment rates.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose to 5.29 francs in New York this morning, and
stayed at above 5.20 francs in most Paris banks today.
</P>
<P>
The LVMH stock rose by 4.42 percent today, while other major
French stocks including Carrefour, Bic, Zodiac and Michelin also
enjoyed substantial boosts. 
</P>
