<HEADLINE> Iran Rules out High-Level Visit to Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister
Mahmoud Vaezi today ruled out the possibility of a visit by
First Vice-President Hassan Habibi to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Vaezi said at a press conference here: "It is simply the
proposal by Iraq. I don't think there will be any visit in the
future."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said that Iran is willing to reciprocate
any friendly gesture, but "there has been no decision yet."
</P>
<P>
Habibi met with Iraqi Vice-President Taha Mohedin in Rome
during the World Food Summit last month, the highest level
contact between Iran and Iraq in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Mohedin extended an invitation to his Iranian counterpart to
visit Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
On October 16, Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani
received Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's special envoy who
voiced Iraq's desire for good neighborly relations with Iran and
for expansion of mutual relations.
</P>
<P>
In return, President Rafsanjani underlined the need for
making efforts to solve the issue of war prisoners and to
completely enforce all articles of the U.N. Resolution 598 on
ceasefire between the two warring parties.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iranian president still regards Saddam Hussein
as the major threat to the peace and tranquility in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He told German Weekly Der Spiegel recently "if they are given
a free hand they will destabilize the region, and they do still
have a lot of capabilities in that regard."
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought an eight-year war from 1980 to 1988. Iran
says it wants to normalize relations with the former enemy, but
there are some big problems, including the prisoners of war, which
block the way for improvement of the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Although the two countries maintained a ceasefire since August
1988, there is no real peace between the two rivals. During the
past years, both sides reported the other's ceasefire violations
to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In the border areas, there exists a "no war and no peace"
state. The two countries still deploy a large number of armed
forces along their borders.
</P>
<P>
Both sides criticized the other for lack of trust and
sincerity in talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
