<HEADLINE> OAU Calls to Support Africa's 60 Million Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 3 (xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) today called on all member states to support activities
in favour of over 60 million disabled persons in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The call was contained in an OAU press release issued here today
to mark the international day of disabled persons which was
proclaimed by the United Nations General Assembly in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The press release said by proclaiming 1981 as the international
year of disabled persons as well as the international decade of the
disabled persons by the UN General Assembly, the General
Secretariat of the OAU, in collaboration with the International
abor Organization (ILO), initiated the creation of the African
Rehabilitation Institution (ARI).
</P>
<P>
The OAU member states, it said, launched the ARI in Harare,
Zimbabwe in 1986 with branches in Brazzaville, Congo and Dakar,
Senegal while those in northern and eastern regions of africa are yet
to be created. It is to be recalled that for ARI to become fully
operational a minimum of nine refitications of the agreement
establishing the institute were required.
</P>
<P>
The institute's governing board chaired by the Secretary
General of the OAU, has initiated and implemented a number of
viable projects in favour of disabled persons in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Most OAU member states are becoming more and more aware of the
need to undeceive the stigmatization of disability issues and in
this connection are promoting the integration of persons with
disabilities in every aspect of social and economic life.
</P>
<P>
The release appealed to those member states which have not
done so to ratify the agreement establishing ARI, as well as to
contribute to the regular budget of the institute in support of its
programs. enditem

