<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Former Conservative minister
Nicholas Scott lost his battle to remain an MP Monday night after
being deselected by his London constituency association.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of about l,000 Tories in Kensington and Chelsea
constituency voted by 509 to 439 to deselect him as their
candidate for the next election.
</P>
<P>
The decision came despite a last-minute appeal to the
association members from more than 100 Tory MPs for them to retain
Nicholas as their candidate.
</P>
<P>
Monday night's meeting was triggered by news that Nicholas'
recent conviction for drink-driving and being found face down on
the pavement in Bournemouth after a drinks party during the party
conference last October.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas admitted to drinking "too heavily" in the past. But he
repeated his explanation that a mixture of painkillers and two
glasses of white wine had led him to collapse on the pavement in
Bournemouth and promised never to touch alcohol again.
</P>
<P>
However, the Tories in Kensington and Chelsea constituency
dismissed his explanation by refusing to pass a vote of confidence
in him.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Dalton, the constituency chairman, said, "My feeling is
sadness for Sir Nicholas. But from the association point of view
it was abundantly clear from the meeting that they were against
him."
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe that the constituency move
will undoubtedly embarrass the Tory government. 
</P>
