<HEADLINE> Iran, Armenia, Georgia, Greece Seek Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran, Armenia, Georgia and
Greece today held the second quadrilateral meeting of deputy
foreign ministers in a bid to expand cooperation in fields of
trade and transportation.
</P>
<P>
The four countries have proposed to establish four committees
on telecommunications, tourism, industry, trade, economy and
energy.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Mahmoud Vaezi, Armenian Deputy
Foreign Minister Sergei Manasarian, Georgian Deputy Foreign
Minister Malkhaz Kakabadzadeh and Greek Foreign Ministry's
Secretary-General Konstantin Gorio are leading their respective
delegations.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that cooperation of the four countries is
politically important because Armenia and Greece were believed to
be historical enemies of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
While Iran is courting friendship of both to find an
alternative for its outlet to Europe, it is worried about the
close ties between Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Vaezi made it clear
that the economic cooperation in the region is aimed at more
closer ties among the regional countries and is not detrimental to
other countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the two-day meeting, Vaezi
said the independence of the Central Asian and Caucasian
republics has provided an opportunity for Iran to go on bilateral
and regional cooperation with the republics.
</P>
<P>
He added that regional cooperation is an priority in the
diplomacy of Iran. Iran believes that regional cooperation is an
important means for guaranteeing peace and security in the region
and that's why Iran is seriously interested in bilateral,
trilateral and quadrilateral cooperation with the regional states.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Republic of Iran, as an important transit route
with abundant energy sources is ready to develop cooperation using
the economic potential of the countries in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Iran, Armenia, Greece and Georgia
are expected to hold meeting in Athens in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
