<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-03 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Israel Agree on New Transport System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Israel agreed here
today on a new door-to-door transport system which would facilitate
trade exchanges between the two sides under the 1994
Jordanian-Israeli peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which had long been cherished by Jordanian
officials and businessmen, came after two months of negotiations
within the context of joint transport committee which oversees
the implementation of the transport deal signed by Jordan and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two countries agreed to dismantle the old
back-to-back system and adopt door-to-door delivery of goods.
</P>
<P>
The accord would also allow Jordanian cement and petrol to be
trucked into Palestinian territories directly via the King
Hussein bridge, which is the key passage between Jordan and the
Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the amendment to the Jordanian-Israeli
transport will eliminate border delays and reduce shipping costs
for the Jordanian exporters.
</P>
<P>
A sub-committee of the Jordanian-Israeli joint transport
committee took the decision last week to replace the inefficient
back-to-back system of transport after months of complaints from
Jordanian exporters.
</P>
<P>
Since the implementation of the transport agreement in June,
Jordanian businessmen have complained that the back-to-back system
- a measure insisted upon by Israel when signing the transport
accord - was an obstacle to bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The system required that consignments of goods moving from
Jordan to Israel or the Palestinian self-rule areas be unloaded
from Jordanian vehicles, inspected by Israeli security and
reloaded onto Israeli or Palestinian vehicles before continuing
to their destinations.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials and businessmen claimed that Jordanian
vehicles would be delayed for hours and, in some cases, days,
although the security check was not supposed to take more than a
couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
The system also brought exporters considerable added expenses,
including a crossing fee, a per ton unloading and reloading
fee, and fines imposed on export companies whose vehicles were
delayed at the border, all of which made Jordanian products
less competitive, they said.
</P>
<P>
The new amendment was widely seen as an incentive to
increase commercial exchanges between Jordan, Egypt, Israel and
the Palestinian self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
