<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Accuse US of Violating Dayton Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Bosnian Serb official
has accused the United States of violating the Dayton agreement in
regard to the arbitration of the controversial town of Brcko in
northern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Serb Prime Minister Gojko Klickovic said today in the Serb
administrative center of Pale that Republika Srpska had been
forced to withdraw its member from the arbitration commission for
Brcko because the United States had put pressure on commission
Chairman Roberts Owen to flout the envisaged rules in the
arbitration and had promised the Muslim-Croat Federation that a
solution in its favor would be reached.
</P>
<P>
Both Muslims and Serbs claimed sovereignty over Brcko, a
strategic town which links the northwestern and eastern parts of
the Serb entity. Under the Dayton agreement, an international
arbitration must be completed concerning the fate of Brcko within
one year after the peace accord was signed last December in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Klickovic told reporters that Brcko was a Serb town and that an
international protectorate was out of the question, according to a
Tanjug news agency report from Pale.
</P>
<P>
He warned that "the price of such decision (against the Serbs)
is a war" and that the U.S. pressure showed that Washington "does
not want peace in the region."
</P>
<P>
The Republika Srpska government decided to withdraw its
representative from the arbitral tribunal on December 1. The
tribunal was comprised of a Serb, a Muslim and an international
arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
The Serb premier expressed the hope that the other members of
the international community would be able to find a just solution
and said the subject of the dispute, which the Dayton agreement
determined as a part of the inter-entity boundary near Brcko, was
now being expanded to the entire region.
</P>
<P>
The Sarajevo Muslim government wants to control Brcko, although
the Dayton agreement envisages that the arbitration commission
should determine the line of separation between Republika Srpska
and the Muslim-Croat Federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
