<HEADLINE> Iran Bans Use of Foreign Words, Names </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran's parliament today ratified
a bill that would make it illegal for both government and the
private sector to use foreign words and names.
</P>
<P>
That is part of the efforts made by the Islamic regime to
fight against the western cultural invasion and to safeguard
the Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The government departments from now on are required to use
only Persian words and names and avoid the use of foreign words
in their official correspondence and speech.
</P>
<P>
The new law also requires Iran's state-run radio and
television to avoid using foreign words and names, and instead use
words authorized by Iran's Academy of Persian Literature and
Language.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Dezfuli, a Persian literature professor at Tehran
University, said that the move by the Parliament would "rid the
language from the invasion of foreign words."
</P>
<P>
Most observers believe that the foreign words will not include
Arabic words that constitute about half of the words used in
the Persian language.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Arabic is the language of the holy Koran,
therefore, it is excluded from the rule.
</P>
<P>
The new law intends to purge the Persian language from words
coming from English, French, German and other western languages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961204.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Stresses Equal Rights for Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali today said that persons with disabilities
should enjoy their civil, political, social and cultural rights on
an equal basis with other people.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the occasion of the International Day of
Disabled Persons, he said, the United Nations has been at the
forefront of efforts to improve the lives of the disabled
throughout the world from its inception.
</P>
<P>
The Organization's Charter affirms the principles of
fundamental freedoms, the dignity and worth of human beings and
the promotion of social progress and better standards of life, he
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly adopted the Universal Declaration Human
Rights in 1948, the World Program of Action concerning Disabled
Persons in 1982 and the Standard Rules on the Equalization of
Opportunities for Persons with Disabilities in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 World Summit for Social Development and other recent
UN conferences have emphasized the need for people-centered
sustainable development, with the eradication of poverty as a
cornerstone. The Copenhagen Declaration on Social Development
points out that people with disabilities form one of the world's
largest minorities, more than one person in 10, and are often
forced into poverty, unemployment and social isolation, he said.
</P>
<P>
In developing countries, most disabled persons are the poorest
in the community, with little or no access to health care or
rehabilitation or support services. Even in developed countries,
studies reveal higher proportions of disabled persons among the
poorest strata of society.
</P>
<P>
"In our continuing effort to build a just society for all, and
in our common endeavor to fight poverty, we recognize that society
needs all persons with disabilities to be active participants," he
said.
</P>
<P>
UN statistics show that a total of 250-300 million people are
severely or moderately disabled in the world. Though the disabling
causes are various, including congenital and postnatal
disturbances, diseases, alcoholism, drug abuse, violence and
injuries, people living in poverty tend to become disabled because
of malnutrition, squalid housing, hazardous occupations and
heightened exposure to violence.
</P>
<P>
UN agencies call on all countries to adopt more effective
prevention measures and increase rehabilitation programs to
empower the disabled with education, vocational training and
health care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
