<HEADLINE> Sotheby's to Stage Sino-British Trade Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Fine art auctioneers of the
Sotheby's are to mount an exhibition on the eve of the historic
hand-over of Hongkong to China by Britain to celebrate the trade
links forged with the Far East over three centuries.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, A Tale of Three Cities: Canton, Shanghai and
Hongkong - Three Centuries of Sino-British Trade in the Decorative
Arts, organized by Sotheby's will run from January 6 to February
8, 1997, according to a press release here today.
</P>
<P>
It will take over all available public space in Sotheby's
London offices which will be extensively remodeled to create a
visually stunning setting worthy of the treasures that will be on
display.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, the first of its kind, will encompass more than
300 carefully chosen and surprisingly diverse exhibits. Most have
been loaned by private and corporate collections in both Britain
and Asia, while others are from museums worldwide, including the
Peabody Museum, Salem, Mass, the company said.
</P>
<P>
The extent of the trade over past three centuries was vast. At
least a hundred million pieces of porcelain reached Britain in the
18th century alone and some of the most spectacular of these will
be exhibited.
</P>
<P>
Among the entries is one for a porcelain service listed in East
India Company's Canton journal for December 20, 1727, as having
been loaded on to the Price Augustus, anchored at Whampoa in the
Pearl River below Canton. The same service survives today and a
teapot from it will be among the exhibits.
</P>
<P>
In addition to every sort of porcelain, the exhibition will
include all of the other decorative art: enamel, silver, pewter,
soapstone, lacquer, painted mirrors, silk, carpets, wallpaper,
furniture and paintings, Sotheby's said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
