<HEADLINE> Beilin to Run For Israel's Labor Party Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Yossi Beilin, an architect of
the Oslo Accords, said today that he will contend for leadership
of Israeli's opposition Labor Party with concrete ideas to solve
the Palestinia-Israeli conflicts in line with Labor veteran
Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Tel Aviv, Beilin said that he
had made the decision since the 73-year-old Peres announced he
would not stand again for the party chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
Beilin reportedly discussed the issue with Peres and some other
party figures after last Thursday's Labor central committee
meeting, which set the date for the end of Peres' term as party
leader and schedued the leadership showdown for June 3 next year.
</P>
<P>
Peres said at the meeting he would support whoever is elected
to take his place. Beilin, a Peres protege, served as deputy
foreign minister and minister of economic planning in the former
Labor govenment.
</P>
<P>
Other candidates include former Foreign Minister Ehud Barak,
former Health Minister Ephraim Sneh and possibly former Interior
Minister Haim Ramon and ex-Tourism Minister Uzi Baram. Barak so
far appears to be the favorite choice.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Beilin said that he would
follow the Peres line without Peres regarding the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I am coming to the arena not with opening positions, but with
some solutions. I am coming with an understanding with the
Palestinians, though not a signed one, about a permanent
solution. I think it is the most important thing," he stated.
</P>
<P>
He continued: "I am coming with very concrete ideas about
the solution about the Arab-israeli conflict, and also about
our social issues."
</P>
<P>
On Jerusalem, Beilin said: "The bottom line for the solution of
Jerusalem would be to distinguish between the Palestinian
definition of Al-Quds and Israeli definition which means actually
the municiple Jerusalem, which was annexed to Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
"Since Al-Quds of the Palestinians is wider than Jerusalem
itself, once there is a Palestinian state -- I don't think there
might be a solution of the Palestinian problem with a Palestinian
state -- they may have their capital in Al-Quds which is out of
the united Jerusalem itself," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't suggest that Israel give up its sovereignty over
Jerusalem," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a historic decision, Israel's then ruling Labor Party
dropped its long-held opposition to the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state in April.  
</P>
</TEXT>
