<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Frozen Lake Found on Moon, Pentagon Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A military spacecraft has
found that the moon has a pond of ice hidden deep inside a crater,
the Pentagon announced here today, increasing chances that people
may someday live on the Earth's satellite.
</P>
<P>
The discovery came from the Clementine spacecraft, which was
launched two years ago mainly for military uses. It used radar
signals to examine the depths of the moon's deep craters and the
discovery of ice was an unexpected byproduct.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon said radio waves were bounced from Clementine into
the crater and back to dish antennas of the Deep Space Network on
Earth. The radio waves could distinguish ice -- at least
tentatively -- because rocks and soil scatter them but the smooth
surface of ice bounces them back in a coherent pattern.
</P>
<P>
Most of the possible ice appears to be at the bottom of the
deepest crater near the moon's south pole, in a pond about 366
meters long and 5 meters to 10 meters deep, it said. And
scientists who led the research believe the water for the ice was
brought to the moon by moist comets that slammed into moon about
3.6 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
The crater, named South Pole-Aitkin basin, is about 2,500 kms
in diameter and up to 13 km deep. It is largely in permanent
darkness so that the water would be trapped as ice in temperatures
near absolute zero, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
"The discovery of ice on the moon has enormous implications for
a permanent human return to the moon," it said, and "the water
from lunar polar ice and oxygen generated from the ice could
support a permanent facility or outpost on the moon."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Apollo spacecraft teams visited the moon in a series
missions from July 1969 to December 1972, but none of them had
found any traits of water.
</P>
<P>
The Clementine is a 75 million US dollar program launched in
January 1994 that uses the moon as a target to test "Star War"
sensors and other devices for a U.S. antimissile missile defense.
</P>
<P>
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA)
co-sponsored the project with the Pentagon and supplied a team of
scientists to analyse information from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
