<HEADLINE> White House: Clinton May Meet Yeltsin Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The White House today
confirmed that U.S. President Bill Clinton is expected to meet
Russian President Boris Yeltsin next year, possibly in the first
half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that Clinton
had raised the matter informally in a letter to Yeltsin. The
letter was delivered by Vice President Al Gore to Russian Prime
Minister Victor Chernomyrdin on Monday in Lisbon, where the two
met at a European security summit.
</P>
<P>
"The president added a personal postscript saying that he
looks forward to seeing President Yeltsin soon," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
"The Russians have said they hope that will be sometime in the
first half of 1997, and I'd say that probably makes a lot of
sense," McCurry said, adding that no date or place has been set.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, a Kremlin spokesman said Yeltsin planned to
meet Clinton in the first half of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
