<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-03 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Calls for More Schools for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel today called for increased schooling facilities
for the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
Marking the World Handicapped Day, he said: " Only 2.5 percent
of the children who need special education benefit from
educational services."
</P>
<P>
The president also said that administrative and legal working
regulations for the handicapped are insufficient and improperly
implemented and must be amended as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Health Minister Yildirim Aktuna said at a meeting in
Ankara that the 6.6 million handicapped people living in Turkey
encountered many problems in cities and that the first step
toward a solution is to meet the needs of the disabled.
</P>
<P>
He noted that protective health precautions would mostly
eliminate congenital handicaps and that marriage between
relatives should be prevented immediately.
</P>
<P>
According to a Turkish official, every year 10,000 handicapped
people applied for jobs in Turkey and that only 5,000 of those were
employed.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has a total of 110 schools and educational and
vocational centers for the disabled, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Necdet Ozturk, chairman of the Turkish Handicapped Foundation,
said that Turkey currently has one confederation, four
federations, and over 50 voluntary organizations providing
services to the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
Ozturk added that 41 percent of the handicaps are the
result of traffic accidents, 21 percent due to birth defects, 24
percent due to occupational accidents and 8 percent due to
terrorist incidents while 6 percent were caused by individual
carelessness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
