<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chavalit in Bid to Reshape Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's new cabinet held its
first meeting Monday after it was sworn in last Sunday and new
Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh made apparent efforts to
restructure the administrative body.
</P>
<P>
At the Monday meeting, the prime minister urged his cabinet
members to stress honesty and transparency and work as a team to
hold collective responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants might be invited to attend cabinet meetings to
explain issues of contention.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit told his ministers that weekly cabinet meetings will
be efficient and punctual and some modern audio-visual equipment
will be introduced to replace the stacks of documents used in
presentations.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that Chavalit also had asked cabinet
members to keep cabinet agendas confidential and stressed that
honesty and confidentiality are necessary to develop discipline
and ethics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ministers at the meeting were reminded to declare
their assets and liabilities in 15 days.
</P>
<P>
Significant personnel arrangements were also made at the
cabinet meeting, with some believed to be radical.
</P>
<P>
Chatichai Choonhavan, leader of the Chart Pattana (National
Development) Party (CPP) who does not take any post in the
cabinet, was confirmed as the special adviser to the prime
minister on economic and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay Virawan has been appointed
chairman of the Council of Economic Ministers, which used to be
chaired by the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Education Minister Sukhavich
Ransitphol will chair the Council of Social Ministers.
</P>
<P>
The economic ministers will meet on Monday mornings and the
social ministers will meet in the afternoon. They will review
those issues to be presented to the weekly cabinet meeting
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Warathep Ratanakorn, a parliamentary member from the New
Aspiration Party, has been nominated as government spokesman and
Chavalit said that the post of government spokesman is very
important in preventing confusion.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the cabinet Monday dissolved 437 committees set up
by the Banharn administration. Visanu Krua-ngarm,
secretary-general of the cabinet, said some of the axed panels
only met once after their establishment.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said he would rely on government agencies, the media
and the opposition to ensure that there was no dishonesty among
his ministers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
