<HEADLINE> Australian Economy Grows At Slower Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian economy was
growing at a slower pace in the September quarter.
</P>
<P>
The national accounts released by the Australian Bureau of
Statistics (ABS) today showed that the economy grew 0.8 percent
seasonally adjusted in the three months to September.
</P>
<P>
This made an annual growth rate of 3.8 percent, down from 4.7
percent in the 12 months to June.
</P>
<P>
However, on quarterly terms, the economic growth rate rose to
0.8 percent in the September quarter from 0.1 percent in the June
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Australian Treasurer Peter Costello said that the economic
growth rate was solid.
</P>
<P>
ABS figures showed that the economic growth in the September
quarter was led by increases in business investment and stocks and
improvement in the country's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
"That's just what you want to see as you look down the track,"
Costello said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the coalition government's strategy was to steer
the economy into a path of sustained growth instead of the
stop-start process of the past decade.
</P>
<P>
"What we need is a nice easy acceleration," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government has cut interest rates twice since July. It
forecast an annual growth rate of 3.5 percent in 1996-97 in its
August budget.
</P>
<P>
Costello and other cabinet ministers have predicted a pick-up
in business investment and economic activities in the first half
of next year.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar rallied in exchange rates against the US
dollar after expectations of a further cut in the official
interest rates failed to materialize today.
</P>
<P>
Local business circles have been calling for the Reserve Bank
of Australia (RBA) to cut interest rates by another 0.5 percent in
order to offset the impact of a stronger Australian dollar on
inflation and exports.
</P>
<P>
Former RBA governor Bernie Fraser helped boost the rate cut
speculations by saying late Tuesday that the RBA should cut the
cash rate by one percent without any risk of raising inflation
pressures. The Australian dollar was knocked down by over one and
a half US cents against the US dollar overnight following his
comments.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar surged above 80 US cents this morning as
the foreshadowed interest rate cut failed to come through.
</P>
</TEXT>
