<HEADLINE> Israel to Continue Peace Process but With Condition: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said here today that the Middle East peace
process would continue, but under a basic condition that the
security of the Israelis is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who arrived earlier today to mark the fifth
anniversary of the landmark 1991 Middle East peace conference,
said the peace process is now facing "obstacles."
</P>
<P>
He made the statement at a joint press conference with his
Spanish counterpart Jose Maria Aznar after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Prime Minister expressed optimism however about the
the peace process by vowing to "push it forward" to find a "just
and lasting solution."
</P>
<P>
Asked if there is any possibility of resuming the
Israeli-Syrian talks, Netanyahu said that "there are no
prerequisites on the part of Israel."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who also met King Juan Carlos, denied that his
country is moving troops on the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the role of the European Union in the Middle East
peace process, Aznar said that the EU had no intention to "exclude
anyone" but to "prod all sides to undertake political dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The Spanish prime minister ruled out the possibility of holding
a second Middle East peace conference in Madrid as claimed by some
press reports, saying there is "no reason" to do so at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
