<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Ports Handle More Cargoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 4 (Xinhua)-- Sri Lanka's three ports of
Colombo, Galle and Trincomalee have handled 18.5 million tons of
cargo during the first ten months of this year, 15.5 percent more
than the same period last year, according to Ports Authority
sources today.
</P>
<P>
The total number of ships which called at the three ports
during this period was 3,092. This was a marginal increase of 1.8
percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Cargoes discharged at Colombo harbor came to 10.9 million tons
while 6.1 million tons were loaded. Colombo port mainly handled
stocks of rice, flour, sugar, fertilizer, cement, crude oil, LP
gas, coconut oil and refined fuel, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 207 ships sailed into Trincomalee harbor in the east
of the country and discharged 974,000 tons of cargo, mainly wheat,
clinker, gypsum and fuel, while loading flour, wheat and bran.
</P>
<P>
Galle harbor in the south of the island nation discharged
194,000 tons, mainly wheat, clinker, gypsum and fuel, and loaded
1,077 tons, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
