<HEADLINE> Thailand's Consumer Price Index Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's consumer price index
(CPI) rose 4.8 percent in November against 4.3 percent in October,
a rise of 0.5 percent caused primarily by a surge in non-food
items, according to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
The CPI for the first 11 months of the year rose 5.9 percent,
up from 4.6 percent in the first 10 months. The latest figures
indicate inflation this year might surpass the Bank of Thailand's
forecast of 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Newly-appointed Commerce Minister Narogachai said to meet the
target, consumer price could rise no more than 1.1. percent in
December.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the November CPI rise to increased prices in the
non-food sector which grew 3.3 percent compared with November
1995. Non-food prices rose 0.9 percent from October's level.
</P>
<P>
Among non-food items, the Thai Commerce Ministry said the
biggest price increases were in tobacco and alcoholic beverages.
Partly because of the imposition of higher excise taxes on tobacco
in October, the prices of tobacco and alcoholic beverages rose 9.8
percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the biggest price increases for food items
were on rice and flour. Rice and flour prices rose 12.4 percent
year-on-year and 1.5 percent month-on-month in November because of
scarcities, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Meat and seafood prices rose 7.3 percent year-on-year, wool and
dairy product prices rose 7.2 percent year-on-year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
