<HEADLINE> Canada Shows Support for France's Fight Against Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien today promised Ottawa's "full support" for France's fight
against terrorism following a bomb explosion in Paris subway.
</P>
<P>
Two people were killed and dozens wounded when a bomb tore
apart a crowded subway car in the city heart Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"You can count on Canada's support, as a committed ally," the
Canadian prime minister told French President Jacques Chirac in a
letter, according to local press.
</P>
<P>
Chretien also extended condolences to the families and friends
of the victims of "this barbarous crime."
</P>
<P>
France, target of frequent attacks of Algerian Islamic
extremists and Corsican separatists, has been in fight with
terrorism for many years.
</P>
<P>
After today's explosion, the French government immediately
revived the "Vilipirate" operation launched after a similar bomb
attack on the Saint-Michel subway station in downtown Paris, which
killed eight people and wounded 159 in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
In response to the bombing, President Chirac ordered a
relentless fight against terrorism in the country and Prime
Minister Alain Juppe, who went to the scene, commanded a manhunt
of the attackers.
</P>
<P>
The bomb blew up when the train was still running in the tunnel
before stopping at Port Royal station near Luxembourg Park, and a
whole car was completely reduced to debris with parts of human
bodies flying all around, said eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
Police have found the debris of a 13-kilogram heavy gas
demijohn, which is supposed to be the bomb.
</P>
<P>
French police said Algerian Islamic extremists are the first
suspect of the attack, judging from the fact that adapted gas
canisters are their usual weapon and their attacks are almost
unexceptionally targeted against civilians, rather than structural
damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
