<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Resident Workers' Kids in Cities Can Go to School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Non-resident labourers in major
Chinese cities are likely to have their children receive regular
schooling similar to local residents, which could rarely be done
before.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing's Fengtai District, where most of the non-resident
workers live, the Beijing Education Administration (BEA) piloted a
regulation this summer to ensure compulsory education for
school-age children whose parents work as itinerant labourers.
</P>
<P>
So far, some 3,869 pupils, or 96 percent of the total, have
been recruited at more than 180 primary schools and middle schools
in the district, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the regulation, children age 7-15 who hold temporary
residence certificate in the district can enter schools by paying
1,000 yuan in tuition each year, and these children attend the
same class with the other children.
</P>
<P>
The regulation is expected to be expanded in the capital's other
district next year, said a spokesman for the BEA.
</P>
<P>
It is also likely to spread to other cities where transient
populations are relatively large, according to the State Education
Commission.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, China had 80 million transient workers, and the number
is still on the increase.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
