<HEADLINE> Sino-British JLG Holds 38th Meeting in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-British Joint
Liaison Group (JLG) opened its 38th meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing before the three-day meeting, Zhao Jihua,
senior Chinese representative on the JLG, said that since the 37th
meeting of the JLG, the two sides have achieved some progress on
many issues through various types of contacts and talks.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that in the year of 1996, both sides on the JLG have
made efforts and solved some difficult and outstanding problems.
</P>
<P>
He said that his experience in JLG's work this year made him
optimistic with the fulfillment of the JLG's work before July 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
He said that with the year of 1997 approaching, the JLG's work
will enter a phase of final sprint.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, there remain many issues for the two sides to
negotiate for solution, and some difficult subjects call for more
efforts from the two sides in the next seven months.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that Hong Kong's smooth transition is the general
trend and popular feeling in the territory and most of Hong Kong
people are wishing for a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese side sincerely hopes that there will be no
more new troubles and obstacles.
</P>
<P>
Zhao added that he is still confident that the two sides on the
JLG will solve in time all the problems related to Hong Kong's
transition through their sincere cooperation and joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
He said he also expects progress to be made in the three-day
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Hugh Davies, senior British representative on the JLG, said
that there are some 200 days to the day for Hong Kong's handover
and there are still a lot of jobs for the two sides to do.
</P>
<P>
He said that the British side will continue to cooperate with
the Chinese side so as to solve the remaining problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
