<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO-- Uruguay's industry grew 11.9 percent during the
third quarter of this year compared with the same period last
year, according to the National Institute of Statistics. This is
the first time in 18 months that industry has reported any growth
in Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina will have to pay off 17 billion
dollars of its external debts in 1997, the Economy Ministry
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
To prevent a concentration of debt maturities, the Argentine
government decided to refinance its external debts by swapping
current outstanding bonds for new ones, even though it would have
to pay higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- David Robledo, president of the Nicaraguan
Coffee-Growers Union, estimated that coffee exports during the
1996-1997 season would generate revenues of 125 million dollars
for the country.
</P>
<P>
He calculated that the national production of coffee this year
would be 1.2 million 46-kilogram (100 pounds) sacks, of which
1.033 million sacks would be exported.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Peru produced 355,363 tons of copper during the first
nine months of this year, representing a growth of 20.6 percent
compared with the same period last year, according to an Energy
and Mining Ministry report.
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Cuba's nickel output reached a record high of 50,000
tons during the first 11 months of 1996. Nickel workers in this
Caribbean country are intensifying efforts to finish December with
a 55,000 tons output, which was the goal established in the annual
plan.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- A new duty-free zone for the sale of petroleum,
which will include a loading terminal and liquid gas depot, will
begin to operate on about 10.5 hectares of the Telfers Island
which is on the Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica exported 332.3 million U.S. dollars
worth of bananas during the first 10 months of this year, a
decrease of 7 percent compared with the same period last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
