<HEADLINE> More Talks Planned on DPRK Nuclear Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Atomic Energy
Agency (IAEA) said today that it would hold a new round of talks
in January next year with the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) on nuclear inspection. as their previous negotiation
failed.
</P>
<P>
The new talks, which are being held because previous
negotiations failed, were announced by Hans Blix, director-general
of the Agency, at the opening session of a two-day meeting of the
IAEA Board of Governors here.
</P>
<P>
Blix said the previous talks between the IAEA and the DPRK, on
September 23-27, had produced no results on the resumption of
nuclear inspection in the DPRK as both sides disagreed on a number
of key issues.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK withdrew from the IAEA in June 1994 about four months
after it agreed to allow the IAEA to inspect seven of its nuclear
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK last October signed a framework agreement with the
United States in Geneva. It agreed to shut down a
graphite-moderated reactor which is believed to be capable of
producing materials used for making nuclear weapons. In exchange
it was to get heavy oil and the lifting or easing of the United
States sanctions against it.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang also agreed to put its frozen nuclear facilities
under the supervision of the Vienna-based IAEA and allow the
agency to carry out inspections of the other nuclear facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
