<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Security Summit Ends in Lisbon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the 54-nation
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) pledged
today to take steps to shape a new security and peace arrangement
for the continent in the coming 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration concluding its two-day summit here today, the
OSCE said it will continue to further enhance the organization's
efficiency as a primary instrument for early warning, conflict
prevention, crisis management and post-conflict rehabilitation in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Premier Antonio Guterres, host of the summit,
described the declaration as a common and comprehensive security
model for Europe for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Key points in the declaration include not to support any state
in using force against any member state, and a guarantee that
foreign troops can only be deployed with the consent of the host
country.
</P>
<P>
"We reaffirm the inherent right of each and every participating
state to be free to choose or change its security arrangement,
including treaties of alliance, as they evolve," the declaration
said.
</P>
<P>
Also at the summit, the 54 member states agreed to renegotiate
the scope and parameters of the 1990 Treaty on the Reduction of
Conventional Forces in Europe. Arms control plays, and will always
play, a crucial role in maintaining peace and security in Europe,
the declaration said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
