<HEADLINE> Indonesian Bank Chief Predicts Economic Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Governor J. Soedradjad
Djiwandono of Bank Indonesia (BI), the central bank, predicted the
country's economic growth would slow down next year but remain
above 7 percent, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on the country's economic prospects for
1997 held here Tuesday, he said next year's economic growth would
be similar to this year's, but slower than the 8.1 percent
expansion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown would result from the tight fiscal and monetary
measures being undertaken now, he said.
</P>
<P>
The annual growth of narrowly-defined money supply began
slowing in June, to 27.5 percent in September, while domestic
liquidity growth declined to 26.1 percent and bank credit grew
19.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Soedradjad said the inflation rate also declined. It was 5.92
percent for the first 11 months of this year compared with the
7.85 percent for the corresponding 1995 period.
</P>
<P>
"All these trends show that Indonesia's economy this year will
slow down a little, but will stay above 7 percent," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
