<HEADLINE> Compaq Tops PC Sales in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Compaq, a leading computer
company in the United States, became the top personal computer
seller on the Chinese market in the first quater of this year,
"China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion was based on a survey conduced by the
International Digital Corp.
</P>
<P>
Intense competition from Chinese manufacturers that have
launched several price wars to win consumer interest, did not
upset Compaq's strategy, which focuses on quality and after-sales
service, said a Compaq official.
</P>
<P>
During the January-September period, sales of Compaq PCs and
servers in China reached 229 million US dollars, about 10 percent
of the country's total PC sales.
</P>
<P>
For China-based PC companies such as Legend Group, Great Wall
and Beijing Beida Founder Corp, Compaq is one of the major foreign
competitors in the marketplace. Other foreign business rivals in
the PC sector now include IBM and AST.
</P>
<P>
To win an upper hand in the battle with foreign competitors,
Chinese PC firms have cut the retail prices of their pentium-based
computers to about 10,000 yuan on the average.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies, however, acknowledge that competing with
Chinese brands on a price basis is not a good idea, since foreign
brands face tariffs and other taxes, said a Compaq official.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Electronics Industry predicts that this year PC
sales are expected to surpass two million units, an estimated
increase of 500,000 units from last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
