<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (Part I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs in Latin America:
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's National Congress Friday approved a
budget totalling 7.865 trillion bolivars (16.734 billion
U.S. dollars) for fiscal 1997 with almost one third of it
allocated for debt servicing. The total expenditures will be at
the same level of the last two years.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian government has taken new measures to
boost exports, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new measures that were put into force Monday,
the National Economic and Social Development Bank is expanding its
role as an important source of financing of Brazil's international
trade.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's auto production rose to 18,200 units during
the first 10 months of this year, up 3.9 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The prices of several perishable and processed
food products increased by 10-80 percent in November, said Arturo
Lomeli, president of the Mexican Association of Studies for the
Protection of the Consumer.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The credit card industry in Colombia had
billings of 3 billion pesos (3 million U.S. dollars) during the
first 10 months of 1996, an increase of 23.8 percent compared with
the same period last year. Its growth was 36.5 percent in 1995 and
43.34 percent in 1994, according to internal Credibanco Visa
figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
