<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference Seeks Answers on Car Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Automakers, insurers and law
enforcers from 30 countries gathered in Warsaw on Monday to find
ways to fight car theft, a booming business for international
crime gangs which costs billions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, which was sponsored by the United Nations,
discussed how to fight slick thieves who spirited vehicles across
frontiers more easily than official agencies could cooperate to
trace and retrieve them.
</P>
<P>
Delegates all stressed the need for cooperation between
government agencies, the experienced sleuths of the insurance
industry and manufacturers who stamped identity numbers on
vehicles and were evolving ever-better security devices.
</P>
<P>
They also sought a quick, effective exchange of information
between countries, and clear procedures for returning stolen
vehicles found in other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
