<HEADLINE> Brazil Backs African to Head United Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's U.N. ambassador said
today that his country wants incumbent U.N. Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali or another African candidate to head the
world body.
</P>
<P>
"Brazil esteems U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali
highly and is not interested in an institutional crisis that would
slim down the entity," said Celson Amorim in Sao Paulo, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
But a second term of the 74-year-old Egyptian diplomat was
rejected by the United States that vetoed him in a 14-1 Security
Council vote on November 19.
</P>
<P>
At present there is a movement among African countries to name
other candidates to ensure Africa's hold to the top U.N. post.
</P>
<P>
Boutros Ghali's five-year term expires on January 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the refugee crisis created by the ethnical conflict between
the Hutus and Tutsis in eastern Zaire, the ambassador confirmed
that Brazil is prepared to form a peace mission for the region.
</P>
<P>
He added that his government is waiting for a redefinition of
strategies by parties concerned on issue since part of the Hutu
refugees are already going back to Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
