<DOCNO> XIE19961204.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-Pakistani Friendship an All-Weather One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAHORE, Pakistan, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A friend in need is a
friend indeed.
</P>
<P>
Both China and Pakistan claim each other to be friends who are
willing and prepared to help the other.
</P>
<P>
And both claim their relationship can serve as a model of
inter-state relations which are based on accepted principles,
mutual interests, and common goals of peace and development.
</P>
<P>
As banners and streamers along and over main Islamabad and
Lahore streets put it, Pak-China friendship is an all-weather one.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin described the
Sino-Pakistani ties as having "withstood the test of international
vicissitudes and enjoyed an all-round growth over the past 45
years" since the two countries established diplomatic relations in
1951.
</P>
<P>
He made this remark while addressing the country's senators on
Tuesday at the parliament house in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
"China and Pakistan enjoy a profound friendship dating back to
ancient times," Jiang said. "Our two peoples have regarded each
other as friends in need and brothers bound by common fate, always
sympathizing with and supporting each other."
</P>
<P>
He added the Chinese government and people are ready to join
their counterparts in further solidifying and strengthening the
friendly and cooperative relations.
</P>
<P>
Friendship proved overwhelming as Jiang materialized his
scheduled state visit even after the Pakistani government
underwent a reshuffle as President Farooq Ahmed Khan Leghari
dismissed Benazir Bhutto from the post of prime minister on
November 5.
</P>
<P>
During his meetings with the Pakistani president, Caretaker
Prime Minister Malik Miraj Khalid and Punjab Province Governor
Khawaja Ahmed Tariq Rahim, Jiang compared notes with them on
issues of common concern as well as emphasizing bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Though his four-day visit was packed with meetings and
discussions and sightseeing tours in two cities, Jiang found a
whole evening to reunite with 11 old friends whom he had worked
with 20 years ago in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He hosted late on Tuesday in his makeshift home at the
Pakistani presidential residence in Islamabad a family-style
dinner of four courses and a soup, the composition of a typical
Chinese dinner.
</P>
<P>
President Leghari, on his part, offered Jiang a ride on his own
special plane and accompanied the Chinese visitor to Lahore, where
he saw him off to conclude his friendship ritual of
airport-to-airport accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani president said relations between the two
countries are not confined to government-to-government ones.
"They are relations that are now firmly rooted, in mutual trust
and respect and in the hearts of our respective peoples," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistanis demonstrated their hospitality to the Chinese
visitor as hundreds of students, folk dancers and musicians
gathered around main crossroads to greet Jiang in both Islamabad
and Lahore while more than 1,000 people availed themselves on a
workday afternoon in Lahore to attend a civic reception given in
honor of the Chinese president.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told Lahore citizens at the reception that the Chinese
visitors have been immersed in the joyous atmosphere of
Sino-Pakistani friendship since they landed in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Pakistani friendship is fortified by deeds.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been cooperating closely in such fields
as politics, military affairs, economy, industry, culture and
education and the Chinese president cited as proof of the friendly
cooperation between the two countries a few projects such as the
Taxila Heavy Mechanical Complex, Karakoram Highway, Saindak
Copper-Gold Mines and Chashma Nuclear Power Plant.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
