<HEADLINE> Chile, U.S.-Based Company to Invest in Gas Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Chile and a U.S.-based company
today signed a 450 million-U.S. dollar deal on a gas pipeline
linking Argentina and Chile.
</P>
<P>
Chilean Economy Minister Alvaro Garcia and Victor Frylinc,
president of the international CMS Energy Corporation, inked the
contract for the construction and operation of the 820
kilometer-long Atacam gas pipeline, which will transport natural
gas from northern Argentina to northern Chile.
</P>
<P>
The investment, including 225 million dollars in hard currency
and an equal amount in associated loans, will be made in a
three-year period.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean minister said that the project, due to come into
service in February 1, 1999, will help stabilize gas supply in
northern Chile.
</P>
<P>
CMS, which engages in oil and gas exploitation as well as power
generation and transmission, has investments in Argentina,
Ecuador, Colombia and Venezuela. 
</P>
