<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Hike Again in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The prices of petroleum products
in the Philippines hiked again by 50 centavos (1.9 US cents) per
liter today.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth increase since the Philippine government
began to implement in August the oil industry deregulation law,
which allows a monthly adjustment of oil prices on the basis of
the Singapore Posted Prices Index.
</P>
<P>
The products covered by the hike include premium gasoline,
regular gasoline and diesel, the most widely used fuel for public
transport in the country.
</P>
<P>
A liter of premium gasoline will now cost 10.76 pesos (41 US
cents) while regular gasoline and diesel are selling at 9.49 pesos
(36 US cents) and 8.07 pesos (30 US cents) per liter respectively.
</P>
<P>
But that is not the end. Bayani Faylona, chairman of the
Philippine Energy Regulatory Board, said another round of
50-centavo increase will be made before the 15th day of the month.
</P>
<P>
This is because the current round of prices adjustment was
delayed by the country's hosting of the informal leadership
conference of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum,
Faylona said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
