<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pre-Hispanic Remains Found in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Pottery from a
pre-Hispanic civilization has been found in recent days in the
province of Catamarca in northwestern Argentina, a local official
said today.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Nazar, director of the provincial Museum of
Anthropology, said the pottery was approximately 1,500 years old
and belonged to the "La Aguada" civilization.
</P>
<P>
The remains were found next to the historical church and museum
of Santa Barbara in Pomancillo, about 20 kilometers from the city
of Catamarca.
</P>
<P>
During a thorough excavation there, experts found pots and
other elements for daily use, all with characteristics of the
agricultural-pottery-making period of the "La Aguada"
civilization. Several pots were in perfect condition.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe the spot was a garbage dump for an ancient
indigenous settlement, which proved the presence of a
pre-Hispanic culture in the area, said Nazar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
