<HEADLINE> Asprilla Lands Second Goal and Booking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Colombian Faustino Asprilla hit
two late goals to help English club Newcastle roll over French
team Metz and enter the UEFA Cup quarter-finals on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle, which drew the first leg of the third-round tie 1-1
in France, won the second leg 2-0 to go through 3-1 on aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Metz fought tenaciously and held out until the 80th minute when
Asprilla broke through to steer the host team out of the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Asprilla, who was booked in the first leg, landed his second
yellow card in the match as he overcelebrated his first goal,
rushing over to the touchline and flinging his shirt over the
corner flag before waving it at supporters.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian was carried off the field two minutes from time
with an injured hamstring.
</P>
<P>
Asprilla fired Newcastle ahead when he headed home Darren
Peacock's cross at the near post.
</P>
<P>
Within two minutes, Asprilla, who scored his five goals in this
season's UEFA Cup, made a solo run before chipping over advancing
Metz goalkeeper Andre Biancarelli.
</P>
<P>
Italian club Inter Milan got a 7-1 aggregate win over Boavista
of Portugal after beating the host team 2-0 in the second leg.
</P>
<P>
Tenerife of Spain also moved into the quarter-finals after
nipping Feyenoord of the Netherlands 4-2 on aggregate. The two
clubs fought to a nil-all draw in the first leg.
</P>
<P>
At Brussels, RSC Anderlecht of Belgium downed Helsingborg of
Sweden 1-0. The first leg ended goalless.
</P>
<P>
Monaco triumphed over Hamburg of Germany 5-0 after winning the
second leg 2-0 in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
In Istanbul, Valencia of Spain defeated Besiktas of Turkey 5-3
on aggregate after the second leg fought to a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
At Gelsenkirchen, Schalke 04 of Germany overwhelmed FC Bruges
of Belgium 2-0 in the second leg, winning 3-2 on aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Brondby crusied into the quarter-finals after crushing SC
Karlsruhe of Germany 5-0. The first leg ended 3-1 in Karlsruhe's
favor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
