<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Invests Heavily in Cotton Cultivation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region in Northwest China has stepped up its efforts to build
more local cotton production bases.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year Xinjiang will have invested 1.2 billion
yuan reclaiming over 80,000 ha of wasteland for the planting of
cotton and turning over 98,000 ha of low-yield cotton fields into
high-yield ones.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000) the
autonomous region will invest a total of 9.4 billion yuan in
cotton production, cultivating some 333,333 ha of wasteland and
upgrading 400,000 ha of low-yield lands.
</P>
<P>
By 2000 Xinjiang is expected to turn out 1.5 billion kg of
cotton. The project will cover 51 counties and cities in 10
prefectures, as well as 116 farms under the Xinjiang Production and
Construction Corps.
</P>
<P>
To reach the goal Xinjiang has formulated a series of
preferential policies to encourage local cotton-growers, and the
price of cotton has been increased by 30 yuan per 50 kg.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has also allocated 400 million yuan as
special funds for water control and nearly 10,000 km of new
irrigation canals have been dug.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, funds have also been provided by the regional
government to launch cotton-seed breeding projects, and build
weather-forecasting facilities, and farm machinery and other
related service networks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
