<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average plummeted 79.01 to 6,442.69 today, the worst loss since
its July sell-off after a late wave of profit-taking on last
month's blue-chip rally.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slim margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume reaching 515.65 million
shares, up from 412.48 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 8.28 to 748.28. The
NYSE's composite index fell 3.29 to 394.85 after making its first
move above 400.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 0.55 to 1,300.37, its first
foray above the 1,300-mark.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange's market value index fell 0.75 to
592.18.
</P>
<P>
The Dow surrendered a 33-point morning gain that briefly put
the blue-chip barometer into record territory.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices rose in the morning, the yield on the 30-year
Treasury bond fell as low as 6.31 percent from late Monday's 6.36
percent. But as bonds retreated this afternoon, the yield rose to
6.35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board research group reported this morning that
its Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose just 0.1 percent in
October. The Commerce Department, meanwhile, reported that new
home sales plunged a surprising 8.7 percent in October to the
lowest level in seven months.
</P>
<P>
The data helped counter Monday's worries about reports of brisk
holiday sales and a big increase in U.S. manufacturing last
month. 
</P>
