<HEADLINE> Ruling Party Confirms Victory in Serbian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Socialist Party of
Serbia (SPS) confirmed its victory in local elections on Tuesday,
saying its coalition had won 151 out of 189 municipal districts in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
SPS Spokesman Ivica Dacic said at a press conference that
repeated voting in a small number of electoral districts cannot
change the overall results and the victory of the left coalition
in both federal and local elections.
</P>
<P>
On November 3, the leftist coalition, comprised of SPS,
Yugoslav Left (JUL) and New Democracy (ND), had won 64 out of 108
Serbia's seats in the lower house of Yugoslav parliament.
</P>
<P>
Dacic said out of the total 7,645 seats in local councils in
Serbia, the leftist coalition and independent candidates won
nearly 5,000 seats, or over 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
The opposition coalition Zajedno (Together) has gained 1,751
seats, or 22.9 percent, and Serbian Radical Party only 308, or
four percent, Dacic added.
</P>
<P>
But Zajedno claimed it had won a majority in the local
elections in the second round of voting on November 17. Zajedno
organized daily demonstrations in Belgrade over the past two weeks
to protest against the court ruling which annulled part of the
results in the run-offs.
</P>
<P>
Due to various errors and irregularities, local elections were
repeated in only 352 polling stations out of the total of 10,076
for 298 seats out of the total of 7,645, Dacis explained, adding
that elections were declared completely null only in the Belgrade
district of Savski Venac, where elections will be repeated.
</P>
<P>
Referring to opposition protest rallies in Belgrade and some
other towns in Serbia, Dacic said the "destructive and violent
nature of the demonstrations was almost the only recognizable
characteristic of the policy of those parties and their leaders
since 1990."
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Belgraders took to the street again on
Tuesday, marching through the city center. The opposition leaders
said they would continue their protest rallies until the
government backed down.
</P>
<P>
Serbian police have arrested 32 protesters for violating laws
during their protest and said they would not tolerate any more the
demonstrations that lasted over the past two weeks, causing
economic losses and jamming traffic in downtown.
</P>
<P>
But some Western countries have warned Serbian leaders to
refrain from using force to crack down the demonstrations or they
would reimpose economic sanctions against Serbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
