<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian-led Team Discovers Stem Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian-led team has finally
identified the elusive parent of all blood cells thanks to
laboratory mice with human immune systems.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of stem cells opens the way to more effective
gene therapy for blood diseases, said team head Dr. John Dick of
Toronto's Hospital for Sick Children.
</P>
<P>
"By pinpointing stem cells, we can test how they can go wrong
and find a way to target them," Dick was quoted as saying by
today's Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Although stem cells are one in a million in the bone marrow,
they are the creators of cells that make all the types of blood
cells, including the immune defenses.
</P>
<P>
Correcting a bad gene in a stem cell would multiply the
correction and pass it along to all future generations of cells,
Dr. Dick explained.
</P>
<P>
The team's finding could lead to more effective gene therapy
for inherited blood diseases such as leukemia, thallassemia and
sickle cell anemia.
</P>
<P>
It will also be important in chemotherapy for tumours anywhere
in the body, Dr. Dick said.
</P>
<P>
Though stem cells are known to exist for years, they look like
other cells, and there was no way of identifying them.
</P>
<P>
Attempts at gene therapy have had to aim at millions of cells,
hoping to affect enough stem cells in the process to make the
change permanent.
</P>
<P>
The team found stem cells by watching which cells created blood
and immune functions in a strain of laboratory mice specially bred
to be born without an immune system.
</P>
<P>
Stem cells have identifying features that include a surface
structure know as CD38. By using an antibody that attaches to that
structure, they can now be easily identified, Dr. Dick added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961204.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tudjman Visits Eastern Slavonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, December 3 (Xinhua) - Croatian President Franjo
Tudjman on Tuesday visited Eastern Slavonia, a region which was
once seized by rebel Serbs but is now being phased into Croatia.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Tudjman and other senior Croatian officials
toured Vukovar, the regional capital which was devastated during
the war with the Serbs and two villages where Croat refugees would
return before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Serbs took control of Eastern Slavonia and formed
their own state when Croatia declared independence from Yugoslavia
in June 1991. In the following war, thousands of Croats were
killed and many more were driven out of the region.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the Croatian government and the Serbs reached an
agreement under which the region would be reintegrated into
Croatia after a maximum two year transitional period under a UN
administration.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with UN Administrator American General
Jacques Klein, Tudjman said in a statement that his visit "is a
sign and proof that the peaceful reintegration of the Croatian
Danubian area into the constitutional and legal system of the
Republic of Croatia is on the right path and progressing well."
</P>
<P>
Tudjman also held talks with local Serb representatives, who
had previously indicated to accept Croatia as their homeland but
also demanded for more minority rights for the Serb population.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, the Croatian customs offices were
re-established along the border between the Eastern Slavonian
region and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961204.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Re-Elect Lott Senate Majority Leader, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Republicans
re-elected Trent Lott Tuesday their majority leader for the next
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after being unanimously chosen as majority leader, Lott
told reporters that the Republican Party and Clinton could work
together on balancing the budget, cutting taxes and other issues.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to working with the president to get
legislative achievements signed into law," Lott said.
</P>
<P>
But Lott also said the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee
would hold hearings on allegations of illegal fund-raising by
Democrats during the recent campaign.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno's decision to not appoint a special
prosecutor to investigate the charges makes a Senate investigation
"even a greater necessity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle was re-elected
today leader without opposition. He said Democrats would make
campaign finance legislation their top priority next year. He said
Democrats would support hearings into alleged fund-raising abuses
if they are "broad-based" and included Republican infractions,
which he refused to describe.
</P>
<P>
Lott, 55, replaced Bob Dole as Republican leader last June,
when Dole resigned to concentrate on his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
Daschle, turning 49 next Monday, will begin his third year in
the job.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans' 53-47 Senate majority has expanded to 55-45 in
the new 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles retained his position today,
while Connie Mack was chosen for the No. 3 job of conference
chairman.
</P>
<P>
Also re-elected for the Democrats were Senators Wendell Ford of
Kentucky, the whip, and Barbara Mikulski of Maryland, who is
conference secretary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
