<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. MCI, British Telecom Apply for $20.8 Bln Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- British Telecom and MCI
requested U.S. federal regulators Tuesday to give green light to
their planned 20.8 billion U.S. dollars merger, which would be the
biggest-ever foreign takeover of a U.S. company.
</P>
<P>
The two telecommunication giants filed the proposal with the
Federal Communications Commission (FCC) today, starting the
requirement process in which consumers and competitors will be
given a chance to comment. The FCC could make a decision within
six months.
</P>
<P>
The planned merger also must be approved by the U.S. Justice
Department, more than 30 state regulatory commissions, British
regulators and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
British Telecommunications is the largest telephone company in
Britain. MCI Communications is the second-largest long-distance
company in this country after AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
The two companies announced agreement November 3 to create a
combined company called Concert to provide communications services
worldwide. The deal would create a company with annual revenue of
42 billion dollars and 43 million business and residential
customers in 72 countries.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T and other rivals contend the merger would hurt competition
and reduce customer choice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
