<HEADLINE> AIDS Clock Exhibition Opens at UN Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- An "AIDS clock", which
ticks off a new HIV/AIDS infection case every 12 seconds in the
world, is on display at the UN headquarters from today through
December 22.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the exhibit is how to prevent the spread of the
HIV infection which leads to AIDS. The display stresses
responsible sexual behavior as a means of preventing HIV
transmission, but it reminds viewers of the need to care for
people living with HIV/AIDS, comfort the bereaved, work for
prevention and seek a cure.
</P>
<P>
It also points out that low-income countries are among the
hardest hit by the HIV/AIDS pandemic, and the least able to cope
with the ravages.
</P>
<P>
They need assistance to provide information and advice on
prevention, as well as care and treatment, the display stressed.
</P>
<P>
UN latest statistics show that there are 22.6 million HIV/AIDS
cases throughout the world and nearly two thirds of them live in
the sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
<P>
Both UN Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali and President
of UN General Assembly Razali Ismail called on controlling spread
of HIV/AIDS in developing countries on Monday when delivering
messages on the occasion of the World AIDS Day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
