<HEADLINE> Irish President on Humanitarian Crisis Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Irish president Mary Robinson
said here today that the world had to learn the lessons of Bosnia
and Rwanda and develop new institutions capable of resolving such
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a gathering of the London English Speaking Union
this evening, President Robinson said that "complex political
crises can not be resolved by short-term humanitarian responses
alone."
</P>
<P>
"International humanitarian aid in itself alone is not the
solution to the problems of the people of Rwanda or other crisis
areas and may simply postpone the problem so that it recurs," she
said.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that the refugees camps established in eastern
Zaire and Tanzania were a response but not a solution, adding "the
camps represented a paralysis of any dynamic towards a true
settlement."
</P>
<P>
She expressed her convictions to build powerful international
institutions to shoulder the task of crisis prevention and
management.
</P>
<P>
President Robinson, who arrived here on Monday for a three-day
visit, received an honorary doctorate from the Coventry University
earlier today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
