<HEADLINE> Algerian Islamic Extremists First Suspect in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Algeria's Islamic extremists
becamed the first suspect in this evening's bomb attack on a Paris
underground train, the RER, in which two people were killed and
many wounded, some of them very gravely.
</P>
<P>
Police have found the debris of a 13-kilogram gas demijohn, a
type of bomb engine which was widely used by the Algerian
extremists in their terrorist attacks at home, and was used in the
attack on a subway train in downtown Paris in July last year.
</P>
<P>
The French government has immediately revived the "Vilipirate
Operation" they launched after the bomb attack on the
Saint-Michel subway station in central Paris, which killed eight
people and wounded 159 in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
Algeria's diehard group of Armed Islamic Group claimed
responsibility for last year's attack on the Paris subway train,
but the terrorists who placed the bomb are still at large now.
</P>
<P>
Although the Corsican separatists have also been launching
attacks on government targets for several months, they never
target people, and regard material damages as rough enough.
</P>
<P>
However, the Algerian Islamic extremists are widely known to be
a group of killers who never hesitate to target innocent civilians
as their victims at home.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that the bomb explosion was so powerful that a
whole district where the RER station was located was shocked.
</P>
<P>
The bomb blew up when the train was still running in the tunnel
before stopping at platform of the station Port Royal near
Luxembourg Park, and a whole car was completely reduced to debris
with parts of human bodies flying all around after the bomb
exploded, said witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Police and firefighters rushed to the scene within two minutes
to put down a big fire from the explosion and rescue the victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
