<DOCNO> XIE19961204.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-03 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Renews Call for Demilitarization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides today renewed his call for demilitarization of his
country.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot president made the appeal at the summit of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), which
is currently underway in Lisbon, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Clerides reiterated his proposal for the demilitarization
of Cyprus which "would go a long way towards diffusing a constant
threat not only to the security of Cyprus but also to the
stability in the region".
</P>
<P>
The president sent a letter to the U.N. Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali in December 1993, proposing the withdrawal
of foreign troops and settlers, the disbanding of the military
forces and the positioning of a multinational force on the island.
</P>
<P>
"It is my belief that the OSCE can promote this proposal
and that it can play an important role in overseeing its
implementation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus "earnestly expects some mechanism for joint OSCE
action in cases of non-compliance with the Helsinki Declaration
of Principles by a member-state", Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
He also backed closer cooperation between the OSCE and other
organizations, such as the Council of Europe, and reaffirmed his
government's commitment to developing further dialogue with its
Mediterranean partners for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In another development, President of the House of
Representatives Spyros Kyprianou recently has demanded to send
packing the two British bases in southern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
After years of struggle against British colonial rule, Cyprus
gained independence in 1960. But under the 1960 Treaty, Britain
retained two military bases on Cyprus' southern coast and other
facilities in various parts of this East Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops landed
and seized 37 percent of the island following an Athens-backed
coup.
</P>
<P>
Repeated UN efforts to reunite the island into a bizonal and
bicommunal federal state have failed to yield any concrete
results.
</P>
<P>
The EU ministerial council decided on March 6, 1995 to
start accession negotiations with Cyprus six months after the
conclusion of the Intergovernmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
However, some EU countries insist that an internal settlement
should be reached before the island joins the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
