<HEADLINE> Mandela Not to Discuss Ties With Taiwan: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- President Nelson Mandela
does not intend to reopen discussions on South Africa's relations
with Taiwan when meeting Taiwanese "Foreign Minister" John Chang
tomorrow, presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said today.
</P>
<P>
Chang arrived here today for talks with South African
officials. He had advanced his trip, originally scheduled for
January, after Mandela's announcement last week that South Africa
will cut diplomatic ties with Taiwan before the end of 1997, and
establish full diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of
China.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will meet Chang in Pretoria tomorrow, Mankahlana told
the South African Press Association (SAPA).
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said: "South Africa wishes to maintain contact
with Taiwan at a level sufficient to facilitate trade, cultural
and other relations."
</P>
<P>
"The decision to establish diplomatic ties with the People's
Republic of China had not been taken lightly," he said, adding:
"It was the result of much consideration and investigation on the
course South Africa should follow."
</P>
<P>
Mandela announced on November 27 that his country's diplomatic
ties with Taiwan will be severed by the end of December 1997, and
other ties with Taiwan will remain intact.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa has become an active participant within
the ambit of the Organization of African Unity and the
Non-Aligned Movement, as well as the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his country's continuation of diplomatic
recognition of Taiwan is "inconsistent with South Africa's role
in international affairs". 
</P>
</TEXT>
