<HEADLINE> European Shares Surge Sharply on Stronger Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Major European stock markets all
surged sharply on Tuesday, with German shares ending at the fourth
record close running and the Paris bourse setting a new high for
the year.
</P>
<P>
The London market rallied strongly and recovered Monday's
losses today, taking its initial momentum from a steady overnight
performance on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that concerns about an interest rates rise and the
rising value of the pound failed to prevent the FTSE 100 index
from ending 23 points higher at 4,061.5.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, share prices climbed higher and set a new record
close, with the DAX-30 share index up 28.38 points at 2,886.98,
helped by buoyant government bonds and the soaring dollar.
</P>
<P>
French shares in Paris surged to their highest level this year
and were 30.48 points up at 2,349.11 at the end of the session,
boosted by a stronger dollar and rising expectations of possible
interest rate cuts in Europe.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 leading British shares closed up 23 points at
4,061.5. The Paris CAC-40 index ended 30.48 points higher at
2,349.11. In Frankfurt, the DAX-30 index finished up 28.38 points
at 2,886.98. 
</P>
