<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-03 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects Proposed Ban on Greek Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides said today that he would not commit himself now to a ban
on flights of Greek military aircraft over Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the statement following a U.S. proposal that
flights of Greek and Turkish warplanes over Cyprus are suspended
for a period of 12 months, according to Cyprus state radio.
</P>
<P>
Carey Cavanaugh, Director of Southern European Affairs at the
U.S. State Department made the proposal to Cyprus Foreign
Minister Alecos Michaelides and the Turkish delegation that is in
Lisbon, Portugal, for the summit of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
The president was quoted as telling the U.S. official that
nothing has been agreed on the U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government, Clerides noted, lays special emphasis
on efforts to settle the Cyprus problem, the start of substantive
consultations to find common ground and also on direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus would welcome any ideas concerning decreasing tension
and would cooperate toward this goal, he added.
</P>
<P>
Clerides stressed that a joint defense principle with Greece
will continue to be strengthened and plans for the construction of
an air base in Cyprus would go ahead.
</P>
<P>
In remarks on the same issue, House President Spyros Kyprianou
said that Cyprus has no obligation to end flights of Greek
aircraft over Cyprus. "Our position is that Greek aircraft fly
over Cyprus legally, with the permission of the government."
</P>
<P>
"But flights by Turkish aircraft over Cyprus are illegal and
contradict international law since they have no permission from
Cyprus," Kyprianou, who is also Cyprus' acting president, told
reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
"If substantive talks begin early next year, the government
would be ready to listen to suggestions about issues relating
to the reduction of tension," he added.
</P>
<P>
Greek and Turkish warplanes have recently taken part in the
military exercises staged by both sides, escalating tension on
this Eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
So far, no comments have been reported on the U.S. proposal by
the Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and seized the northern third of the island following
a short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
